Bemporad et al. (2006) studied an event on 2002 November 26, at the time of a SOHO-Ulysses quadrature campaign, which made their work unique because the SOHO-Ulysses data set allowed them to analyze a current sheet structure from its lowest coronal levels out to its in situ properties. The event occurred over the northwest limb and produced a CME with speed at the front increasing from 90 to 420kms−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
