				\begin{document}$2.5\times 10^{5}~\mbox{km}$\end{document} (0.36 R⊙).

The SXR emission above the solar limb at altitudes ranging from 0.1 to 0.3 R⊙ from the solar surface during the 2002 November 26 event was also observed by RHESSI (e.g., see Saint-Hilaire et al. 2009). This high-altitude coronal X-ray source (HACXS) lasted for 12 hours, and the corresponding temperature peaked around (1.0∼1.1)×107K\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
