In a two-ribbon flare process, individual flare loops do not stay at the height when they are newly formed, but decrease to a lower altitude at which their shape is more potential, and the earlier the loops are formed, the faster the loops shrink (Lin et al. 1995; Lin 2004). In the impulsive phase of HXR, the shrinkage of individual loops is much more significant than the growth of the loop system resulted from accumulations of individual loops such that the speed of the former could be close to 200kms−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
