				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$23^{\circ}$\end{document} behind the west limb when the event occurred, and several instruments in space observed both the flare and the associated CME. These instruments include XRT on Hinode, TRACE, SECCHI on STEREO A, and LASCO on SOHO. GOES did not classify the flare because most of the flare was located behind the limb. Occulting of the brightest structures of the flare by the solar limb allows the less bright structures above the active region to be recognized more easily. As the eruption was in progress, the CME moved away from the Sun like a cart wheel, so this CME is also known as the “cart-wheel CME”.

