				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$400~\mbox{km}\,\mbox{s}^{-1}$\end{document}, which agrees well with the typical Alfvén speed in the lab environment. Fig. 14
Experimental set-up for laser-driven magnetic reconnection performed by Zhong et al. (2010). Four bunches of long pulse (1 ns) lasers are focused on both sides of a thin Al foil target. Shadowgraphy and interferometry are used to diagnose the plasma evolution with a short pulse (120 ps) probe beam (shown as a green dotted line). The MR occurs between the two laser focus spots, and is detected by three X-ray pinhole cameras. The reconnection outflow/jet can thus interact with a pre-set Cu target. X-ray spectra from the heated plasma are recorded by a crystal spectrometer set in front of the target. From Zhong et al. (2010)Fig. 15
